SIMPLE: portion
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Portion
<hw>Por"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from L.
<ets>portio</ets>, akin to <ets>pars</ets>, <ets>partis</ets>, a part.
See <er>Part</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
divided off or separated, as a part from a whole; a separated part of
anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A part considered by itself, though not actually cut
off or separated from the whole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These are parts of his ways; but how little a <qex>portion</qex>
is heard of him!</q> <rj><qau>Job xxvi. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Portions</qex> and parcels of the dreadful past.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A part assigned; allotment; share; fate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lord of that servant . . . will appoint him his
<qex>portion</qex> with the unbelievers.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xii.
46.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man's <qex>portion</qex> is to die and rise again.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The part of an estate given to a child or heir, or
descending to him by law, and distributed to him in the settlement of
the estate; an inheritance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give me the <qex>portion</qex> of goods that falleth to me.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke xv. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A wife's fortune; a dowry.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Division; share; parcel; quantity; allotment;
dividend.</syn> -- <usage><er>Portion</er>, <er>Part</er>.
<xex>Part</xex> is generic, having a simple reference to some
<xex>whole</xex>. <xex>Portion</xex> has the additional idea of such a
division as bears reference to an individual, or is allotted to some
object; <as>as, a <ex>portion</ex> of one's time; a <ex>portion</ex> of
Scripture</as>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Portion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Portion
<hw>Por"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Portioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Portioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate or
divide into portions or shares; to parcel; to distribute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>portion</qex> to his tribes the wide domain.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To endow with a portion or inheritance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him <qex>portioned</qex> maids, apprenticed orphans, blest.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1117 --></p>

<p><ent>Portioner</ent>⟦br⟧
